I traveled from India to Scotland to fulfill a childhood dreamâseeing the real "Hogwarts Express"  featured in the "Harry Potter"

The Hogwarts Express, officially known as "The Jacobite," runs twice a day, meaning it crosses the famous viaduct four times. 
Here are the time-windows when the train passes over the iconic viaduct featured in the Harry Potter films:

1. 10:40 am - 11:00 am: âCâ-shaped viaduct view from the viewpoint.
2. 1:15 pm - 2:00 pm: Linear-shaped viaduct view.
3. 2:45 pm - 3:20 pm: âCâ-shaped viaduct view.
4. 5:45 pm - 6:15 pm: Linear-shaped viaduct view.

Whether youâre on a group tour or driving through Scotland on your own, youâll need to reach the "Glenfinnan Viaduct & Monument Car and Coach Parking" (Google Maps).

- Parking fee: Â£5 per day.
- From the parking area, itâs a 20-minute easy hike to reach the viewpoint.
- The viewpoint is at the top, either on the left or right depending on the trainâs direction. 
Ask the on-duty volunteer for guidance which viewpoint to go(left or right) or simply follow the crowd, as thereâs only one trail for each viewpoint.

Reaching Glenfinnan Viaduct & Monument Car and Coach Parking

If youâre on a road trip through Scotland, itâs best to add this stop towards the end of your journey:

On your last day: Portree (Isle of Skye base) -> Glenfinnan Viaduct -> visit Glencoe Valley + Glen Etive (for a night stay or just passing through) -> Glasgow.

- Portree to Glenfinnan Viaduct: 2 hrs 45 mins drive.
- Glencoe to Glenfinnan: 1 hr drive.

Riding the Jacobite Express

- Itâs mandatory to purchase a roundtrip ticket (no one-way tickets available).
- Ticket prices:
 - Adult Standard class roundtrip: Â£65, Child: Â£36
 - Adult First class roundtrip: Â£98, Child First class: Â£64
 
- 2024 Season: Tickets can only be purchased at the station (first come, first served). No online tickets are available.
- The one-way train ride lasts 2 hours and 10 minutes.

INCREDIBLE JUMP FROM SPACE!! -17 MARCH 2016

This incredible jump is the Red Bull Stratos mission on March 17, 2016. Austrian skydiver Felix Baumgartner jumped from a high-altitude balloon in the stratosphere, about 24 miles above the Earth's surface. This daring leap was part of a scientific project to study human limits and gather data for future space travel. Baumgartner broke the sound barrier during his freefall, reaching a maximum speed of approximately 843.6 miles per hour. It was a historic moment in space exploration and parachuting, showcasing the possibilities of pushing boundaries.

Credit - Redbull and BBC
